, England":"Mashbury, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Cambridge, , Gloucestershire, England":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Mashbury, Essex, England":"Mashbury, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Everard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Everett  .","French (northern), Walloon, and Dutch: variant of French and Walloon   Evrard  , Dutch   Everhard  .","Americanized form of German   Eberhardt   or   Everhardt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Everett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal names <i>Everard</i> and <i>Everet</i>. These might occasionally be from the Old English form of the name, <i>Eoforheard</i> (from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hardy, brave’), but many bearers of this name were undoubtedly Normans, who took it from the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Eburhard</i>, <i>Everhard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Thomas Everard was born in 1303, in Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Everard in 1323, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Mashbury, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1303–":"1303–Surnud","1299–Male":"1299–Surnud","1323–1349":"1323–1349","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1349":"1349","1303":"1303","1323":"1323","1299":"1299","Leverington, ,